defs.docs: # Chrono: Date and Time for Rust

defs.name: prelude
defs.docs: A convenience module appropriate for glob imports (`use chrono::prelude::*;`).

defs.name: offset
defs.docs: The time zone, which calculates offsets from the local time to UTC.

defs.name: None
defs.docs:
Given local time representation is invalid.
 This can occur when, for example, the positive timezone transition.

defs.name: Single
defs.docs: Given local time representation has a single unique result.

defs.name: Ambiguous
defs.docs:
Given local time representation has multiple results and thus ambiguous.
 This can occur when, for example, the negative timezone transition.

defs.name: LocalResult
defs.docs: The conversion result from the local time to the timezone-aware datetime types.

defs.name: single
defs.docs: Returns `Some` only when the conversion result is unique, or `None` otherwise.

defs.name: earliest
defs.docs: Returns `Some` for the earliest possible conversion result, or `None` if none.

defs.name: latest
defs.docs: Returns `Some` for the latest possible conversion result, or `None` if none.

defs.name: map
defs.value: fn <U, F> (self, mut f: F) -> LocalResult<U>
defs.docs: Maps a `LocalResult<T>` into `LocalResult<U>` with given function.

defs.name: and_time
defs.docs:
Makes a new `DateTime` from the current date and given `NaiveTime`.
 The offset in the current date is preserved.

defs.name: and_hms_opt
defs.value: fn (self, hour: u32, min: u32, sec: u32) -> LocalResult<DateTime<Tz>>
defs.docs:
Makes a new `DateTime` from the current date, hour, minute and second.
 The offset in the current date is preserved.

defs.name: and_hms_milli_opt
defs.value: fn (self, hour: u32, min: u32, sec: u32, milli: u32) -> LocalResult<DateTime<Tz>>
defs.docs:
Makes a new `DateTime` from the current date, hour, minute, second and millisecond.
 The millisecond part can exceed 1,000 in order to represent the leap second.
 The offset in the current date is preserved.

defs.name: and_hms_micro_opt
defs.value: fn (self, hour: u32, min: u32, sec: u32, micro: u32) -> LocalResult<DateTime<Tz>>
defs.docs:
Makes a new `DateTime` from the current date, hour, minute, second and microsecond.
 The microsecond part can exceed 1,000,000 in order to represent the leap second.
 The offset in the current date is preserved.

defs.name: and_hms_nano_opt
defs.value: fn (self, hour: u32, min: u32, sec: u32, nano: u32) -> LocalResult<DateTime<Tz>>
defs.docs:
Makes a new `DateTime` from the current date, hour, minute, second and nanosecond.
 The nanosecond part can exceed 1,000,000,000 in order to represent the leap second.
 The offset in the current date is preserved.

defs.name: unwrap
defs.docs: Returns the single unique conversion result, or panics accordingly.

defs.name: Offset
defs.docs: The offset from the local time to UTC.

defs.name: fix
defs.docs: Returns the fixed offset from UTC to the local time stored.

defs.name: TimeZone
defs.docs: The time zone.

defs.name: Offset
defs.docs:
An associated offset type.
 This type is used to store the actual offset in date and time types.
 The original `TimeZone` value can be recovered via `TimeZone::from_offset`.

defs.name: ymd
defs.value: fn (&self, year: i32, month: u32, day: u32) -> Date<Self>
defs.docs:
Makes a new `Date` from year, month, day and the current time zone.
 This assumes the proleptic Gregorian calendar, with the year 0 being 1 BCE.

defs.name: ymd_opt
defs.value: fn (&self, year: i32, month: u32, day: u32) -> LocalResult<Date<Self>>
defs.docs:
Makes a new `Date` from year, month, day and the current time zone.
 This assumes the proleptic Gregorian calendar, with the year 0 being 1 BCE.

defs.name: yo
defs.value: fn (&self, year: i32, ordinal: u32) -> Date<Self>
defs.docs:
Makes a new `Date` from year, day of year (DOY or "ordinal") and the current time zone.
 This assumes the proleptic Gregorian calendar, with the year 0 being 1 BCE.

defs.name: yo_opt
defs.value: fn (&self, year: i32, ordinal: u32) -> LocalResult<Date<Self>>
defs.docs:
Makes a new `Date` from year, day of year (DOY or "ordinal") and the current time zone.
 This assumes the proleptic Gregorian calendar, with the year 0 being 1 BCE.

defs.name: isoywd
defs.value: fn (&self, year: i32, week: u32, weekday: Weekday) -> Date<Self>
defs.docs:
Makes a new `Date` from ISO week date (year and week number), day of the week (DOW) and
 the current time zone.
 This assumes the proleptic Gregorian calendar, with the year 0 being 1 BCE.
 The resulting `Date` may have a different year from the input year.

defs.name: isoywd_opt
defs.value: fn (&self, year: i32, week: u32, weekday: Weekday) -> LocalResult<Date<Self>>
defs.docs:
Makes a new `Date` from ISO week date (year and week number), day of the week (DOW) and
 the current time zone.
 This assumes the proleptic Gregorian calendar, with the year 0 being 1 BCE.
 The resulting `Date` may have a different year from the input year.

defs.name: timestamp
defs.value: fn (&self, secs: i64, nsecs: u32) -> DateTime<Self>
defs.docs:
Makes a new `DateTime` from the number of non-leap seconds
 since January 1, 1970 0:00:00 UTC (aka "UNIX timestamp")
 and the number of nanoseconds since the last whole non-leap second.

defs.name: timestamp_opt
defs.value: fn (&self, secs: i64, nsecs: u32) -> LocalResult<DateTime<Self>>
defs.docs:
Makes a new `DateTime` from the number of non-leap seconds
 since January 1, 1970 0:00:00 UTC (aka "UNIX timestamp")
 and the number of nanoseconds since the last whole non-leap second.

defs.name: timestamp_millis
defs.docs:
Makes a new `DateTime` from the number of non-leap milliseconds
 since January 1, 1970 0:00:00 UTC (aka "UNIX timestamp").

defs.name: timestamp_millis_opt
defs.docs:
Makes a new `DateTime` from the number of non-leap milliseconds
 since January 1, 1970 0:00:00 UTC (aka "UNIX timestamp").

defs.name: datetime_from_str
defs.docs:
Parses a string with the specified format string and
 returns a `DateTime` with the current offset.
 See the [`format::strftime` module](../format/strftime/index.html)
 on the supported escape sequences.

defs.name: from_offset
defs.docs: Reconstructs the time zone from the offset.

defs.name: offset_from_local_date
defs.docs: Creates the offset(s) for given local `NaiveDate` if possible.

defs.name: offset_from_local_datetime
defs.docs: Creates the offset(s) for given local `NaiveDateTime` if possible.

defs.name: from_local_date
defs.docs: Converts the local `NaiveDate` to the timezone-aware `Date` if possible.

defs.name: from_local_datetime
defs.docs: Converts the local `NaiveDateTime` to the timezone-aware `DateTime` if possible.

defs.name: offset_from_utc_date
defs.docs: Creates the offset for given UTC `NaiveDate`. This cannot fail.

defs.name: offset_from_utc_datetime
defs.docs: Creates the offset for given UTC `NaiveDateTime`. This cannot fail.

defs.name: from_utc_date
defs.docs:
Converts the UTC `NaiveDate` to the local time.
 The UTC is continuous and thus this cannot fail (but can give the duplicate local time).

defs.name: from_utc_datetime
defs.docs:
Converts the UTC `NaiveDateTime` to the local time.
 The UTC is continuous and thus this cannot fail (but can give the duplicate local time).

defs.name: Utc
defs.docs:
The UTC time zone. This is the most efficient time zone when you don't need the local time.
 It is also used as an offset (which is also a dummy type).

defs.name: today
defs.docs: Returns a `Date` which corresponds to the current date.

defs.name: now
defs.docs: Returns a `DateTime` which corresponds to the current date.

defs.name: FixedOffset
defs.docs: The time zone with fixed offset, from UTC-23:59:59 to UTC+23:59:59.

defs.name: east
defs.docs:
Makes a new `FixedOffset` for the Eastern Hemisphere with given timezone difference.
 The negative `secs` means the Western Hemisphere.

defs.name: east_opt
defs.docs:
Makes a new `FixedOffset` for the Eastern Hemisphere with given timezone difference.
 The negative `secs` means the Western Hemisphere.

defs.name: west
defs.docs:
Makes a new `FixedOffset` for the Western Hemisphere with given timezone difference.
 The negative `secs` means the Eastern Hemisphere.

defs.name: west_opt
defs.docs:
Makes a new `FixedOffset` for the Western Hemisphere with given timezone difference.
 The negative `secs` means the Eastern Hemisphere.

defs.name: local_minus_utc
defs.docs: Returns the number of seconds to add to convert from UTC to the local time.

defs.name: utc_minus_local
defs.docs: Returns the number of seconds to add to convert from the local time to UTC.

defs.name: Local
defs.docs: The local timescale. This is implemented via the standard `time` crate.

defs.name: today
defs.docs: Returns a `Date` which corresponds to the current date.

defs.name: now
defs.docs: Returns a `DateTime` which corresponds to the current date.

defs.name: naive
defs.docs: Date and time types which do not concern about the timezones.

defs.name: NaiveDate
defs.docs:
ISO 8601 calendar date without timezone.
 Allows for every [proleptic Gregorian date](#calendar-date)
 from Jan 1, 262145 BCE to Dec 31, 262143 CE.
 Also supports the conversion from ISO 8601 ordinal and week date.

defs.name: MIN_DATE
defs.docs: The minimum possible `NaiveDate` (January 1, 262145 BCE).

defs.name: MAX_DATE
defs.docs: The maximum possible `NaiveDate` (December 31, 262143 CE).

defs.docs:
Makes a new `NaiveDate` from the [calendar date](#calendar-date)

defs.value: fn (year: i32, month: u32, day: u32) -> Option<NaiveDate>
defs.docs:

defs.docs:
Makes a new `NaiveDate` from the number of days since January 1, 1 (Day 1)

defs.name: from_num_days_from_ce_opt
defs.docs:
Makes a new `NaiveDate` from the number of days since January 1, 1 (Day 1)

defs.docs:

defs.name: overflowing_add_signed
defs.docs:
Adds given `Duration` to the current time,
 and also returns the number of *seconds*
 in the integral number of days ignored from the addition.
 (We cannot return `Duration` because it is subject to overflow or underflow.)

defs.name: overflowing_sub_signed
defs.docs:
Subtracts given `Duration` from the current time,
 and also returns the number of *seconds*
 in the integral number of days ignored from the subtraction.
 (We cannot return `Duration` because it is subject to overflow or underflow.)

defs.name: signed_duration_since
defs.docs:
Subtracts another `NaiveTime` from the current time.
 Returns a `Duration` within +/- 1 day.
 This does not overflow or underflow at all.

defs.name: SubsecRound
defs.docs:
Extension trait for subsecond rounding or truncation to a maximum number
 of digits. Rounding can be used to decrease the error variance when
 serializing/persisting to lower precision. Truncation is the default
 behavior in Chrono display formatting.  Either can be used to guarantee
 equality (e.g. for testing) when round-tripping through a lower precision
 format.

defs.name: round_subsecs

Return a copy rounded to the specified number of subsecond digits. With
 9 or more digits, self is returned unmodified. Halfway values are
 rounded up (away from zero).

defs.name: trunc_subsecs
defs.docs:
Return a copy truncated to the specified number of subsecond
 digits. With 9 or more digits, self is returned unmodified.
